In 1994, a group of people were interested in studying the past started the Jamestown Rediscovery Archeologists Project.The project was designed to discover the secrets of the James Fort in Virginia. For over 200 years, people thought that the fort had been washed away by a river. Some discoveries in the area hinted that it might still be around.       The first objects were found in 1861. They found uncovered armor and weapons. They also discovered the floors of buildings. The people doing the study used computer mapping software to make an image of the area. That's when they finally found James Fort!       The first thing they found was a set of marks on the ground. The marks showed where the fort's walls used to be. The archeologists also found eleven cellars and ten buildings all within the border of the fort. Today, the group finds nearly one million objects each year!       Archeologists used a lot of tools. Most of them were used to clean off dirt off the artifacts. They used picks, shovels, whisks, dustpans, knifes, wheelbarrows, skim shovels, and trowels. archeologists                                             Archeologists are people that dig holes and find artifacts from the past to learn about life back then.They need tools to do it they use shovels,picks,whisks,duspans,wheelbarrows,skim shovels,trowels, and a knife.     We are now going to learn about finding Fort James.        In 1994, a group of people interested in studying the past started the Jamestown Redicovery Archaeological Project.The project was designed to discover the secrets of the James Fort in Jamestown, Virginia. for over 200 years,people thought it had been washed away by the river. Some dicoveries in the area hinted that it might still be around.      The fort was built in 1607 when settlers came from england to start a new life. Most belived that James Fort was built near the river. It was easier to dock ships there, so it made sense that the settlers would choose that spot. However, objects found nearby suggested the fort was located further away. The new spot problably gave the settlers more protection from enemy ships.           the first objects were found in 1861 those items were armor and weapons.They also discovered the floors of buildings.Over 100 years later,a group effort to find the exact spot the fort was built began.           The national park service led a five year study of the area to figure out how the land was used. They knew this would help them decide where to look for proof of the fort. The people doing the study used computer mapping software to make an image of the area.        That's when they finally found James Fort! The first thing they found was a set of marks on the ground.The marks showed where the forts walls used to be. Between all the stories they heard and read,and drawings they made,the archeologists knew it would be shaped like a triangle.They made maps and found out that the fort streched all the way to the river.Then they realized there were stone ledges built over the river. The ledges were designed to hold cannons. The archeologists also found eleven cellars, dozens of burial sites,and ten buildings within the border of the fort.

The Job of an Archeologist           An Archeologist is a person who works to find objects that belonged to a person who lived long ago. There are many different teams who do different jobs for this process. The first team finds the place they will be digging at. The next group focuses on the digging itself. The last group studies the results.                 The first team finds the place where the diggers will be digging. That is probably the most important job of them all because if the first group chose a place in the middle of nowhere, where there is nothing to be found, the hunt will not work. They also need something to look for. If they don't know what to look for and don't have information about it, the hunt won't work either. So, they find the place where they will hunt and map it out in detail on a 3D computer. Then, they record the information so that the diggers know what the place looked like before the digging began. That is the first groups job.                  The second team is the digger team. They have a very important job too, because they are the ones do the actual digging. They use very special tools that are great for delicately digging through the earth. They must be very careful in digging, because if they dig too hard, they could destroy the artifacts or even miss them. The most common tool used by the archeologists is the Trowel. Archeologists use it to look at the different layers of soil. Some more tools archeologists use are the pick and the shovel. They are both used to dig through the earth and look closely at the dirt. Once the diggers find what they think is an artifact, they give it to the third team.                  The third team receives the artifact that the diggers find and look very closely at it. They have special tools for that as well. They examine the artifact, determine who it belonged to, and got most of the credit. The diggers got a lot of the credit too, though. This is what the third team does.                       So this is what archeologists do. They have three different teams that work together to find artifacts that belonged to people long ago. All the teams must work extremely hard to get the job done. If I were to be an archeologist, I would want to be in the third team because you get to examine the artifacts the second team finds. I wouldn't want to be in the second team because you have to dig for a long time and give a lot of your effort into it. This is what archeologists do.

Digging up Geore Washington's Past                      Most of  what we know about George Washington comes from his time as a soldier and president . Biographies don't have very much information about his childhood . That's changing , however . Recent discoveries at Washington's childhood home have helped historians know more about Washington as a boy .                How did archeologists find all of these things that were in Washington's house all those years ago ? The process of digging at the Ferry Farm is a careful one . Each year , many teams will work on the site . There can be up to 35 people on a team ! The first team maps the area using 3D computers that can track what's in the ground. The information is recorded so that people will know what it looks like before people started digging. Another team focuses on the actual digging and the place the team does the digging is called a dig . Those  archeologists start their dig with what are called skim shovels .           The shovels are small ,flat, and sharp that they can remove thin layers of soil is then placed in a box with a half-inch screen at the bottom .This lets the dirt fall out and the artifacts stay in.The diggers also use a process called troweling .Troweling is when archeologists use small shovels,paint brushes ,and wooden picks to remove dirt .It can take up to two weeks to dig a 25-square-foot section ! Another team spends days in the lab studying the objects that are found . The whole process is slow and tiresome , but it is worth it .           No one knew exactly where the Washington house was located since the actual building was long gone .However, archeologists believed that the base under the house was still there .They started digging in 2003.It took over a year , but they finally found it . The first  buildings they found were the kitchen, slve quarters, and storage houses .           The discovery of Washington's house is important for many reasons . First , it gives the citizens of the United States a better understanding of who George Washington before he was famous . We also began to know why he made the decisions he did . Another thing it does is help historians learn about the type of  life Colonial Americans lived . All of these things are key parts of our past as Americans .

Now you must be wondering, ' How do archeologists find and dig up these artifacts, and what do they normally use?', well, hold your horses, because now I about to tell you! Actual archeologists do not just find these artifacts by themselves. No way that would happen! Then finding the artifact or artifacts would take forever! No, that actually doesn't happen, because archeologists work together as a team to discover the artifacts. As a matter of fact, some teams can have up to thirty-five people on the team! No joke! But what do archeologists USE to find these items? You must be wondering. Well right now I shall list a couple of tools that archeologists and their team use to dig up these items. Pick and shovel are used to start most digs to dig near the artifacts. Whisk and dustpan are used to brush dirt off the artifacts, and to clear dirt away from the excavation site, too. The knife is used for careful digging and also to scrape dirt from around the artifacts. The wheelbarrow is used not only to move items from one place to another, also to sometimes to carry dirt away from the excavation site to someplace elsewhere. The skim shovel is used to remove thin layers of soil, carefully, with a flat edge made for that specific purpose. Now I will be telling you about the last tool that is commonly used by archeologists, and it is called the trowel. The trowel is actually probably the most commonly used tool in archeology. It is normally used to cut and scrape to view the different layers of soil, there. Well, there is one more thing used for digging up artifacts in archeology, some teams use 3-D computers that can track what is inside what is in the ground right before the digging, so that you will not have to dig in a place where there isn't anything that you were looking for.Well, now I believe that I have covered all the tools! George Washington was a heroic leader and it's so fascinating to learn about his life, where he got is ideas, and where he lived. With that information, when the archeologists found burnt potterey, they had a more educated guess on where the Washingtons had built there house. Archeologists have complicated, time consuming jobs, but it is all worth it to find impressive artifacts that tell us about our past.          To begin, the work that archeologists do is usually complicated. One team creates a map with 3D computer that tracks what is underground. The other team digs with a small, flat, and sharp shovel. Another idea is that it is worth all this hard work. With all this work, archeologists can help people learn more about our past. Lastly, their jobs are very time consuming. It took two weeks for archeologists to dig up a 25 square foot place! It also took 5 years to find James Fort!          Overall, an archeologists job is complicated, time consuming, but worth it. Even though with all this hard work archeologists work hard.

How we knew dinosaurs that lived here before us ? Well, we know these things because of archeologists. They are the ones who dig up these artifacts and study them. Archeologists have lots of jobs.                    First, one job an archeologist might have is that they have to find an interest that people have from the past that  can not be proved like how people were interested in studying the past of the Jamestown Rediscovery Archeological Project. When they find an interest they look for the spot where it might be. They also check if any other archeologists from the past had found artifacts that are part of the interest such as the Jamestown where archeologists found objects in the area in 1861. Then they get ready to dig the site or area . That is the first step.                     Next, before they can dig  they must find the spot where it might be. They also might find  out how the land was used  and how they used resources to find the right spot. As an example; like when the National Park led a 5 year study of the area to figure out how the land was used for the Jamestown Project. To find the right spot and area they use technology to make an image such as computer mapping software and 3D computers that can track what is underground.The information is stored away and recorded so the archeologists know what the area looked  like before they started digging.This the second step.                       Finally, they do the actual digging of the site. Another team does the real digging of the artifacts because of the computers and the technology they use the archeologists know right where to dig and what artifacts to expect. The area they do the actual digging is called the dig. They use skim shovels to start the digging of the dig.The shovels are very small ,flat, and sharp  so that they can remove the thin layers of soil , one at a time. The soil that has been dug is placed in a box with a 1/2 inch screen  in the bottom. It lets the soil fall out but the artifats stay in. They also use the process called troweling . Troweling is when the archeologists use tiny shovels, paint brushes, and wooden picks to remove the soil. This process takes a lot of hard work and time. It can take up 2 weeks just to dig a  25- square -foot section! Another team of archeologists study the artifacts at a lab and that can take a long time. The tools used by archeologists are; pick and shovel, whisk and dustpan, knife, wheelbarrow, skim shovel and teh trowel. The Search of James Fort   By: Sami Siddiqui       Introduction: How the Topic Started       A gang of people were fascinated to start the Jamestown rediscovery Archeological Project. The activity is used to explore the hidden secrets of James Fort of Jamestown, Virginia. A rumor spread that a river washed away for the past 200 years. Still, a few clues have been found, which made people think that it is still standing.       Brief History of James Fort       The fort was designed in 1607 at the time when English people settled in the colonies to start their lives again. Many people thought that fort was built near a river to have simple docking. Archeologists later found artifacts that led them into a wrong course. The spot for the fort was clever because it kept more protection of enemy ships.                The Reasearch       The first few items were found in 1861. The revealed objects were a few swords and suits of armor. Archeologists also found floors of buildings. Many, many years later, clues led to where the fort was located.   The National Park Service were paying much attention to the fort. The people were imaging the area to be sure the area was correct.       The Founding of James Fort       It turned out to be right! The James Fort was actually found! The archeologists left tracings and markings so the location can be found many times again and again. Maps were developed, and evidence was shown that the fort was built by the river. The archeologists uncovered 11 cellars, many burial sights, and ten buildings constructed by the fort!       Conclusion        In conclusion, James Fort is a mysterious place that had covered secrets found by the archeologists. In my opinion, James fort is an interesting place to learn and study about.

To continue, after the teams who map the area are finished with their part of the job, the team that will do the actual digging come. This team begins by first using small, sharp, and thin shovels called skims to carefully remove the many layers of the dirt. After completing that, the diggers start a process called troweling. This process is carried out with shovels wooden picks to remove more layers of the soil. The entire process of digging can take up to two entire weeks, just for a small 25 square foot section of the soil. This stage is hard, and tedious, but it is one of the most important stages of the large job.       The final stage of the tiresome (but fun) process that archeologists carry out is analyzing the artifacts that were found by the digging team. Technicians spent lots of time to use their expensive equipment to complete the hard work the two other teams did, and actuly learn from the many artifacts found. After many months of hard work, analyzing is complete. The long job has been ended, and all the teams, and all of the other scientists become thankful for the important information the hark work of the many archeologists has found.       To conclude, becoming an archeologist is a painful, but fun, process which helps everyone discover important things in the covered past. Archeologists Historical Discoveries               This research will be about archeologists historical discoveries. They will be finding Fort James, digging up George Washington's past,finding the spot of Ferry Farm, and the tools used.                            In the year of 1994, a group of people were going to study the past that had started the Jamestown Rediscovery Archaeological Project or J.R.A.P. This project has been designed to discover secrets of James Fort in Jamestown, Virginia. For more than 2 centuries, people thought that Fort Jamestown was washed away by a river. A couple of discoveries in that area made a hint that it may still be around. The first discoveries were found in the year of 1861. The archeologists that were studying the Jamestown Fort found uncovered armor and weapons. Some also found the floors of buildings. Over a century later, a group found the exact spot where the fort was built.           A lot of what we know about George Washington comes from the time when he was a soldier and our first president. Biographies barely have any information about George Washington's life as a child. That has changed. There has been recent discoveries about where Washington's childhood home is and how it has helped historians learn more about our first president's history as a child.           Lots of people have lived on the land where Ferry Farm once was for over 12,000 years! That is a long time. The location of Ferry Farm makes the land a perfect place to build a home for families. However, it is no surprising that George Washington's father, Augustine Washington, moved his family there. At that time George was just 6 years old! Because the actual building was long gone, no one knew exactly where the Washington's home was located.         The tools that were used by the Archeologists to find their discoveries such as George Washington's home were used carefully,so that the objects that were found wouldn't break, because they were very old. These tools are, pick and shovel. (Most digs start with these two tools. Used to dig into the earth, close to artifacts.) Whisk and dustpan.(Used to brush dirt off the artifacts and clear away from the excavation site.) The knife. (Used for careful digging and to scrape dirt from around the artifacts.) The wheelbarrow. (Used to move items from one place to another or to carry dirt away from the excavation site.) The skim shovel. (A shovel with a flat edge used to carefully remove a thin layer of soil with each scoop.) Last but not least, the trowel. (Probably the most common tool in archeology. Used to scrape and cut to view the different layers of soil.)           Throughout this research a lot has been learned. In this research archeologists have found Fort James. they have dug up George Washington's past. They have found the spot of Ferry Farm. They also have used very important tools for these discoveries. That is the end of this research on Archeologists Historical Discoveries.

The Job of an Archeologist             You may stop and think, 'What is the use of an archeologist?'. A lot of people think that archeologists are of no use. Sure, the job is tiring and slow. But it's worth it. Today I will explain why archeologists are important and what they do during the job. I will also explain how archeologists find information about ancient people and my opinion on archeologists.              Archeologists may seem useless because all they do every day is just dig and look for buried things in the ground all day long. It may seem like that but their job is actually very useful to the world. Looking at source #2, it says 'Most of what we know about George Washington comes from his time as a soldier and president. Biographies don't have very much information about his childhood.' People don't have much information about his childhood but thanks to archeologists, that's changing. Archeologists dig in places where George lived as a child to find out what kind of life he led when he was young. Aren't you curious to find out about this great American's childhood? Thanks to present archeologists we are finding more about George Washington's life everyday. It is not just George Washington however, it is also to find out more events from the past of a lot of famous people. From source #1, archeologists have found more information about Fort James. Archeologists are still studying ancient people and let's hope we can find more about more famous people. That is the use of an archeologist. To find out more about famous people. Now you know the use of an archeologist.             To find out information of an ancient person, archeologists use lots of tools. Archeologists work in teams that can hold up to 35 people. Lots of teams work together on a site. This is what archeologists do when trying to dig. The first team maps the area with 3D computers that can track what is underground. The information is recorded so that people will know what the area looked like before people started digging. Another team that is called a dig, does the digging in the area. They first use skim shovels that are so small, flat, and sharp, that they can remove thin layers of soil, one at a time. The soil is then placed in a box that has a half-inch screen at the bottom. This lets the dirt fall out while the artifacts stay in. The digs use another process called troweling. Troweling is a process that archeologists use small shovels, paint brushes, and wooden picks to remove the dirt out of artifacts. Surprisingly, it takes 2 weeks to dig up a 25-square-foot section! The final team spends days in the lab studying the objects that are found. This whole process is slow and tiresome, but it's worth it if it's to shape history. Now you know how hard it is to find historical artifacts. The whole thing is so slow that you need to have a lot of patience if you want to be an archeologist. This is how people dig up the past.              'How do archeologists find out about events in history when all they're doing is looking at objects?'. That might be a question frequently asked and here's the answer. Looking at sources #1 and 2, They found lots of things left behind in the ruins of James Fort and George Washington's childhood home. The pieces of burnt pottery they found at Ferry Farm showed that there was a fire there and the metal toys they found at Fort James proved that there were children there. Looking and studying these things actually tell you how people lived in those days. That is how people find out how ancient humans lived in those times.             I think that an archeologists job is fun, even though you need to have a lot of patience. Digging and studying ancient artifacts that have been touched by famous people would also make me feel special. I think that an archeologist's job is very fun and I would love to do it.             Now you know all about the job of an archeologist. I hope this essay has been of use to you. Thank you for reading this!

Once a group of people that were interested in studying the past started the Jamestown Rediscovery Archaeological Project. But the project had been designed to discover the secrets of the James Fort in Jamestown Virginia. For over 200 years people thought that the fort had been washed away by a river. Some discoveries in the area hinted that it might still be around.        But the fort was built in 1607 when the settlers came from England to start a new life the kids thought that was really interesting. Most believed that the James fort was built near the river. It was easier to dock ships there so it made sense that the settlers would choose that spot. But however objects found nearby suggested the fort was located further away. The new spot probably gave the settlers more protection from enemy ships the kids that are looking for some things that they don't know about it looks like they get allot of information that tells them allot about what happened back then.   And the first objects were found in 1861. Archeologists are the names for scientists who study objects from the past uncovered armor and weapons. They also discovered the floors of buildings. Over 100 years later a group effort to find the exact spot where the fort had been built.               Now the National Park Service led a five-year study of the whole area to figure out how that land was used. They knew that this would help them decide where to look for proof of the fort. The people doing the study used computer mapping software to make an image of the area.               That's when they finally found James Fort!!! The first thing they found was a set of marks on the ground. The marks showed where the Fort's walls used to be. Between all the stories they heard and read about and drawings they made the archeologists knew that the fort would be shaped like a triangle. They made maps and found out that the fort stretched all the way to the river. Then they realized there were stone ledges built over the river. The ledges were designed to hold canons. The Job of an Archeologist          An archeologist studies objects from the past.  They use different tools to find objects from the past.  These objects are called artifacts.  Archeologists have found many artifacts.          Some artifacts archeologists find are sometimes places or buildings.  In 1944, a group of people intrested in the past stated the Jamestown Rediscovery Archeological Project.  Their project was to find James Fort in Jamestown, which people thought washed away by a river.  James Fort was built in 1607 by colonists.  They built near a river so it was easier to dock ships.  But, with the artifacts found, it is hinted that Fort James was located further away.  Some of the first artifacts they found were armor and weapons.  They had also found floors of the buildings.  Over a century later, a group effort to find the correct location of Fort James began.  The National Park Service` led a five-year study of the area to find out how the land was used. This would help them find proof of the fort.  The people doing the study used a computer mapping software to make an image of the area.  That's when they found James Fort.  After finding James Fort they also found cellars burial sites and buildings within the border of the fort.          Another place archeologists dug for is George Wasington childhood home. Washington's home was built on Ferry Farm, but no one knows exactly where it was located.  However, archeologists believed there was a stone base under the house.  They started digging in  2003.  It took over a year, but they found Washington's childhood farmhouse.  They also found the kitchen, slave quarters, and storage houses.            Tools used by archeologists are pickaxes, shovels, whisks, dustpans, knives, skim shovels, and trowels.  The pickaxe and shovel are used in the beginning of the dig to dig near artifacts. Whisks and dustpans are used to brush away dirt from the artifacts and the excavation sites.  The knife is used for careful digging and to scrape dirt off of the artifacts.  Wheelbarrows are used to carry dirt and items from one place to another.  Skim shovels have a flat edge to carefully remove a thin layer of dirt with each scoop.  Trowel is the most commonly used tool in archeology. it is used to scrape and and cut to view layers of soil.          These are what past archeologists did, found, and used.

In 1861, there were the first objects found in Jamestown by archeologists. Around 100 years later, a different group began to search for the exact location of the James Fort. They believed it was located near a river, so it would be easier to dock ships there. However, in 1994, archeologists began searching again in Jamestown for the James Fort, which people believed for many years that it was washed away by the river they thought it was near. By judging the objects that they found close to the river, the archeologists thought that it was located somewhere farther away from the river, so they were safer from any enemies. They finally found Jamestown by looking at a group of marks on the ground, and decided that it was triangular, and was located near the edge of the river. Now the archeologists find many artifacts near where the fort really is.           Many archeologists wanted to learn more about the home of George Washington, because they didn't know much about his childhood. They knew that the Washington's lived on the Ferry Farm, and moved there when he was six years old. Although they didn't know the exact location of the house, they began to dig in 2003 at the Ferry Farm. It took more than a year when they finally found the Washington's home. They found the kitchen, storage houses and slave quarters first, then years later, found the main farmhouse. Archeologists said there were other houses built on the Ferry Farm, so they needed the proof that it was really George Washington's childhood farmhouse. They said that there was a fire at his house, because they dug up some burnt pottery, along with part of a pipe. Which was more proof that it was the Washington home, because George smoked. An archeologist's job is to find and recover items from the past, or artifacts. Archeologists most likely work in groups, rather than working by themselves. They work like this because the artifacts are very delicate historical items, and all of these items are crucial to discovering the history of mankind. Archeologists hold a lot of responsibility to keep the artifacts safe, clean, and whole.       While working, an archeologist needs many tools. Here are some of the tools that an archeologist might use in their work: a pick and shovel (to dig into the earth, close to the artifacts), a whisk and dustpan (to brush dirt off the artifacts and clear the dirt away from the excavation site), a knife (to dig carefully and scrape dirt off the artifacts), and a wheelbarrow (to carry away dirt from the excavation site or to move something from one place to another). These tools often help archeologists in their work.       How do these archeologists find all these artifacts? The first thing they do is have one team of archeologists use 3D computers to map the area. Then the information is recorded so that people will know what it looked like before they start digging. A different team of archeologists does the actual digging, and they place where the team digs is called a dig. These archeologists start digging with skim shovels, a small, sharp, and flat shovel that can remove small layers of soil at a time. The soil that is dug up is placed in a box with a half-inch screen at the bottom. The screen lets the dirt fall out of the box, while the artifacts stay in. The digging team also does a process called troweling. What is troweling? Trowling is when the archeologists use wooden picks, paint brushes, and small shovels to get rid of dirt. All of these processes are cautious ones, and only professional archeologists should perform them.       As you can tell, an archeologist's job is tough, requires maximum intelligence, and is lined with caution. Beacause if almost anybody else finds artifacts in their backyard and trys to handle them like an archeoloist would, say good-bye to the artifact (well, say good-bye to the artifact being whole, at least). And that, kids, is why you should never dig for artifacts in your backyard!

The first mission to a successful archeology project, is the identification of the material. Scientists use a special computer to track down and locate the item that they want to discover. Using sophisticated radar can be helpful, they use X-ray machines. Given all these privileges, scientists get a rough idea of what the material looks like underground, so it can help them see if they have found it the right thing.         This leads to the process of digging. After they have found the item, it is time to dig it out. Here is where a LOT of what archeology means, comes into action. The digging starts with archeologists using a tool, called a Skim Shovel. These are special shovels that are small, flat, and sharp. All this makes the shovel dig out a layer of soil. The dirt is dropped into a box with a small, so that the soil can leak out by itself. Then comes a bigger tool, the shovel. This kind of shovel takes larger amounts of soil off the ground. The box will overflow, because of the bigger quantity of soil, and dirt. This drags another tool in; the wheelbarrow. A wheelbarrow is sort of like a wagon, which is essential because the soil amount has increased. When the archeologist finally hits a surface, he or she takes out the other tools for the job; the whisk and the dustpan. These are used to brush the dust off the surface so that they can see what the surface is really like. If it is the object they are looking for, they are successful. Digging for History        Do you know what archeologists are? Do you know what they do? Do you know what tools they use? Well then lets get started! This fun essay will show you what they are, what they do, and what tools they use.            Archeologists, the name for scientists who study objects from the past, and uncovered armor and weapons. In 1994, a group of people interested in studying the past, stared in Jamestown. The project was designed to discover the secret of James Fort in Jamestown, Virginia. For over 200 years, people thought the fort had washed away by the river. Some discoveries in the area hinted that it might still be around. This paragraph will be about the tools Archeologists use to find lost artifacts.  Some of the larger tools would be the Pick and Shovel, the Wheelbarrow, and the Skim Shovel.  Some of the smaller objects include the Trowel, the Whisk and Dustpan, and the Knife.  The Knife is used to dig carefully and push dirt away from the artifacts.  The Trowel is used to do some cutting and scraping to have some sort of a view of the different layers of soil.  The Whisk and Dustpan is probably used after you find the artifact it brushes off the dirt on an artifact.  The Pick and Dustpan is used to start the dig and get down close to the object, while the skim shovel scrapes thin layers of dirt with it's flat edge and dumps it into the wheelbarrow which then takes it away from the excavation site. Being an archeologist is not an easy job.  Once you are notified that there are artifacts somewhere.  You can't just start digging, or else you don't know where to dig.  First, you have to map the area with computers, then you can start digging with the skim shovels.  The skim shovels start removing layers of dirt, but be careful, you don't want to skim too far or else you might break the artifacts.  You could also start with a pick and shovel, once you are close to the artifacts.  You are very likely to use a trowel to remove the last few layers of soil. At this point, you will have to be super careful, or else you could easily break the artifacts.  If the soil surrounding the artifact is hard, you would use a knife to carefully scrape off the dirt.  If the dirt is soft or loose, you would use a whisk and dustpan.  As you can see, being an archeologist requires skill, but is still partially based on luck.  Why luck?  Well, you could be digging for 15 minutes and of found 43 treasure chests, while you could've been digging for 9 years and only found a piece of metal.  In conclusion, being an archeologist is not always easy.

The Life Of An Archeologist   By: Nick Alonzi              The life of a archeologist seems full of excitement and just searching for cool objects. It is, but it's a lot more then that. Even before the work happens it takes years to plan out the location. Then it's tiresome hours of ?finding objects in the ground on a 3D computer. Finally months of digging in the dirt for those objects. In this report you will learn the forgotten work of the archeologists.          The one of the hardest things an archeologist has to do is search out the coordinåtes of the ruins. In a article I read it took a couple years to begin the search. I once met with a professor, he told me that 'in many of my archeological digs that it took 2-3 years to come up with the location.' He said that 'it takes many calculations. We have to go off of recent reports. Sometimes we go off of findings. One time we had a huge lead when we met up with a business man who said that their is a certain place with artifacts lying around everywhere.' There also is another flaw in this work. Say your calculations are off. You could dig up an entire place for nothing. You lose a bag load of money for nothing. You now have to reconfigure your calculations and spend another 2-3 years on calculations. This is one of the many tiresome events that occur as an archeologist.          Another tiresome act that occurs is the hours of watching a screen for any sign of object in the ground. This can be as boring as staring at a wall because      There is no game, website or anything to do but watch the screen. If you are hungry or go to the bathroom you need to call someone over to take your shift. Then the other person encounters the boredom that you were experiencing. If you sit to long, your butt falls asleep. I personally hate that.    Those were 4 things that may or may not occur if you are at this post. Not only those scary life threatening events but if the fates hate you that day they will either shut down your machine or make you dig up a tin can. If you dug 15 feet into the ground for that you would be furious. This is 5-6 things that can ruin your day in at least 10 minutes.          Finally the toughest part of them all. The dig. This part is the hardest because you have to dig in the hard earth. Yes, there may be machines, but, there always won't be. Imagine breaking your back everyday. Digging and digging and digging till you find the artifact. 95% of archeologists say that they needed 30 day back therapy after the dig. Yes, back therapy. 30% also said they either needed physical therapy for a couple months or needed back surgery. Imagine that! That's why only the crazy, dedicated, and genius have a career as a archeologist. Now you may call it. The dig.          As you can see you are wrong. A job as an archeologist is a crazy career not just fun and games. If you are interested in the job and have at least two of the traits I have listed above here are the simple steps.       Get a bag load of money Take 2-3 years to plan your archeological dig. Get a huge group of crazed workers. Take hours and hours of time on a 3D computer looking for artifacts. Start to dig and dig to find the objects. Schedule a physical therapy appointment.         Now you know the basics, and always remember them, they will come in handy! See you at the dig!

Informational Report on a Job of a Archeologist                                                             By: Brianna Geiger               Have you heard of an archeologist?  Have you ever been an archeologist?  What is an archeologist?  What do they do?  All of those questions might be going through your head right now, but I will answer all those questions.  Anyways, to be an archeologist is a lot of work.  Also they have to take a lot of classes to know what to do .  The good thing is that they can get a lot of money for selling all their precious artifacts to dealers.  Therefore, the job of an archeologist can be very complicated.               First of all, to be an archeologist is a lot of work.  You have to work all day long, which can be very tiring.  Also to be an archeologist can be very slow because you have to dig up artifacts that are very precious.  Sometimes you have to use paintbrushes, small shovels (skim shovels), and wooden picks, this is called troweling.  Even if you have a big group digging to find artifacts, it can take over two weeks to find and dig up something.  Furthermore, archeologists have a lot of work.               Secondly, to be an archeologist you have to take lots of classes.  For example, you have to learn about history to know where and what happened in the past.  They do this to know where to dig and what to dig/look for.  You also have to take archeology to learn how to dig and to dig properly.  There is also a lot more classes you have to take to be an archeologist, but that would take a while.  Lastly, you have to take a lot of classes to be an archeologist.               After all, you can get lots of money if you sell the artifacts to a dealer.  This is the good thing about being an archeologist-you get a lot of money out of it.  If you sell the artifacts to a dealer, they can give you lots of money for the artifact(s).  If the artifact(s) are very old you can get a lot of money for it.  If the artifact(s) are not really really old you will get less money, but still a lot of money.  All in all, this is the good part about being an archeologist- you get a lot money.               To sum it up, to be an archeologist is very complicated.  Archeologists get a lot of money.  You have to take a lot of classes to be one.  The on thing that is good is the money that you get.  Well, I hope you learned something new about the job of an archeologist.

For more than 200 years people believed that Fort James had been carried away by a rushing river, but now there starting to doubt that theory. The was believed to be built either by a river or father away to be protected from enemies. The first artifacts were found in 1861. Archeologists found armor, weapons, floors and even ceilings of the fort. Now people are trying to find the exact place the fort was at. Since other houses had been built there they needed proof it was young George's house. Records say the house burned down and they found burnt pottery. They also found clay pipes which they know Washington loved to smoke them. The archeologists have to be very careful while digging and handling artifacts. One wrong move and an important part of our history could be destroyed in seconds. Up to 35 people could be working on one site. They also use Highly advanced computers. They even let kids help out!       Finally I'll tell you about tools they are the pick and shovel used to dig the earth close to objects, whisk and dustpan used to dust the dirt off artifacts, knife used for careful digging near the artifact, Wheelbarrow is used to move artifacts or dirt away from the dig site, skim shovel used to remove a thin layer of soil and finally the trowel used to scrape, cut or view the soil differently. It might be at James Fort, George Washington's house, or maybe they are looking for dinosaur fossils.                      Archeologist are separated into three teams with up to 35 people. The first team maps the area using 3D computers that can track what is underground. This information is used to get a look of what the area looks like before team two starts digging. Team two is the team that does the digging and gets the artifacts out of the ground. The archeologist start the dig with a skim shovel. This shovel is flat, small, and sharp. This makes it so it can remove different, thin layers of soil one at a time. Then they place it in a box with a half inch screen at the bottom, so dirt can fall out with the artifact still in. They also use other tolls besides for the skim shovel, like the trowel, pick and shovel, wheelbarrow, and more.              Archeologist jobs take a long time to do. Archeologists         Archeologists  study objects that have been used by historical figures many many years ago. Most of the time archeologists study from 5-10 years or more on a site, such as the one they studied about George Washington. They started digging in 2003, and over a year later, they found up to three rooms. They were the kitchen, the slave quarters, and storage houses. They had heard that there was a fire that happened in the Washington house, and they needed proof that this plantation was actually Geaorge Washinton's house. After lots of digging, the archeologists found burnt pottery, and parts of a clay pipe. Since George Washington smoked clay pipes, it was now obvious that this plantation had belonged to the Washingtons.      Usually on digging sites, there are a big number of teams/groups. There can be up to 35 people on a team!  Archeologists use up to six sets of tools. They are the Pick and Shovel, which most digs start with these tools, used to dig in the earth close to the artifacts. Second there's the Whisk and Dustpan, used to brush the dirt off the artifacts and items gently. Third there's the knife, used for careful digging and used to get the dirt out from hard to reach places. Fourth there's the Wheelbarrow, used to move objects and artifacts away from the site or to carry dirt out of the site. Fifth, there's thw Skim Shovel, which is a shovel with a flat surface used to ccarefully remove thin layers of dirt and/or soil with each scoop. Finally there's the Trowel, which is probably the most common tool used by archeologists, used to scrape and cut to view different layers of soil. And that is what archeologists do.

In conclusion, the archaeologists wanted to find out the secrets of Fort James.             The fort was built in 1607. Settlers came from England to start a new life. People would built ships, start businesses, and built new homes. They would even grow crops like corn, tabacco, and other crops. It was easier to dock ships there, and settlers choose the spot there. Settlers also started alot of businesses. The spot even gave people the protection from enemy ships. In conclusion, the settlers came from England to James Fort to start a new life.                 The objects were founded located further away from the fort. The achaeologists found the first objects in 1861. They study the objects that uncovered that armor and weapons in James Fort. They discovered it was under the floors of the buildings. The armor and the weapons were used to protect the fort from enemies, who tried to attack the fort. Maybe, the settlers put the armor and the weapons under the floor of the building so no one will still them. Plus, the enemies won't know where they hid the armor and the weapons. The first thing they have to do is find a set of marks on the ground. The second thing, to do is the marks showed where the fort's walls used to be. All the stories peole heard that drawings they made, the archaeologists knew that James fort formed like a triangle. They believed that the settlers used the stone ledges to built over the river. Plus, the designs on the ledges were canons. The most amazing part is, that the archaeologist found eleven cellars, dozens of burial sites, and ten buildings all with the border of the fort. The job of an archeologist is a very interesting job.  You have to plan the digs very carefully and make sure everything is in perfect order.  There are three main groups in archeology with up to thirty-five people in each.        The first team maps the area using 3D computers that can track what is underground.  That information is recorded so that the diggers know what is underground before people started digging.  This was very helpful to the discovery of Fort James.  The archeologists needed a good map of the area, so they used the computer mapping software.  The 3D computers are a very helpful tool when looking for the spot where archeologists want to start digging.        The second team focuses on the actual digging.  The site where diggers dig is called a dig. Those archeologists start digging with a tool called a skim shovel.  A skim shovel has a flat edge and with each scoop removes a thin layer of soil.  When archeologists dug up some artifacts from George Washington's childhood, the first tools they used were skim shovels.  The second tools they used were shovels, paint brushes, and wooden picks.        The third and last team works in the lab.  They study the objects that were found.  They have to work very carefully so none of the artifacts would get broken.        I hope you have learned about archeologists and what they do!

An Archeologist's Job                                    You make think an archeologist is just someone who digs up stuff, but that is not true. An archeologist is someone who uses artifacts to study the past. Archeologists have a hard job to do.                     Archeologists have to be organized, careful, and use their time wisely to get their job done. It can take long times to complete a dig. First, a team will map the area using special devices so that they can see what is underground. This helps the people know what the area they are digging in looked like before they started digging. Then another team starts the actual digging. They start the dig with a special shovels which are very small, flat, and sharp. With these shovels they remove only small layers of dirt. Once they have that soil, they will put it in a box where the dirt will fall out while the artifacts stay in. Another thing they may do is troweling which is done with paint brushes, small shovels, and wooden picks. It can take two weeks to remove a twenty-five-square-foot area with troweling. Finally, a different team will study the things they found. It is a very slow process.                      Archeologists use many different tools. They will use a pick and shovel to dig down into the Earth. A whisk and dustpan are used to tidy up the artifacts or clear dirt from the dig-site. Also they will use a knife for careful digging and scrapping dirt of the artifacts found. A wheelbarrow is used to transport dirt or the artifacts to another place. Taking a thin layer of dirt is the skim shovel's job. A very common tool, the trowel, is used to scrape and cut so you can see the different layers of soil. Those are common tools used be archeologists.                      Archeologists have found artifacts in many different places. George Washington's house is one. They have found things there that have helped them learn new things about George Washington's life. It also helps us know about him before he became famous. Another place is James Fort. We now know about the settler's every day life and challenges.                      Archeologists are actually very important. They help us know what we know about history. They are more than just diggers.

WHAT THEY DO       An acheologist is the kind of scientist who likes to 'dig' depper.   They discover artifacts of all kinds from tall caves, to deep oceans. Artifacts are objects from the past. Archeologist ue the artifacts to discover many things from our history. Such as, Gorge Washingtons old house, The exact spot were for jams was built, why the Titanic sank, and more! Our children, and ourselves will be able to learn about htese artifacts and what it was like back then. Pick and Shovel: to usualy dig through dirt or rocks   Whisk and dustpan: To gently clear off dust from artifacts   Knife: Used for CAREFUL digging and for scraping off dirt from hard to reach places on an artifact. ?Archeology      ??By Elizabeth Starkey         Have you ever wondered what it would be like to be an archeologist or what tools they used? Or how we can learn from archeologists? Well, it is very interesting to be an archeologist, in my opinion, and it is very hard!         It's interesting and boring because of the things you might find. Some people have found remains of historical artifacts like walls of Fort James or broken pottery from George Washington's house. You could also find clothes and other things that people used back then. Who knows what you could find out there? Only time will tell! It could also be boring when you don't find anything for a while. You could dig up a large area of dirt and not find anything.         Archeologists used many types of tools for many different reasons. One tool that archeologists use most often is the 'whisk and dustpan.' These are used like a dustpan at home! You would use the whisk to clear off the dirt on the artifact. Then, the dirt would go into the dustpan. Picks and shovels are often used to start the search. They use the pick to chip away at the dirt. The shovel is used to move the dirt out of the area (most likely into the wheelbarrow). The knife is used for carefully scraping dirt off of the artifact. The wheelbarrow is just used for a simple transport of dirt to somewhere else; most likely away from the digging site. A skim shovel would be used for removing a thin layer of dirt from the earth. The most often tool on a digging site would be a trowel. This is just a smaller version of a shovel used for digging and to show the different layers of dirt.         If you have ever wondered what we could learn from archeology? Time to put that question to rest! We can learn a lot from archeologists! One example would be that we could find out what colonial life was like. Archeologists found George Washington's house that he lived in when he was a boy. They found burnt, broken pottery, which indicated that there was once a fire at George Washington's house. We have also found some remains of Fort James. Archeologists started digging up armor and weapons that would indicate that Fort James was built in that area. We can also see what it was like to live in Fort James, like several cellars, burial grounds, and toys for children, all in the same area.         As you can see, we could learn a lot from archeology and fro the people who dedicate their time to helpus learn about colonial life.

An archeologist has a special and important job. They have to plan out what they are trying to find, carefully and slowly follow the directions, and do research. When archeologists want to find out more about something in the past, they get a team for the digging process and finding information. For them to find more about the past they have to do research on it just like the people did when they found Fort James. They have to know where the historical place was, what are they trying to find, and what happened to the historical place to start digging or looking for clues.                   When archeologists are ready and they have done there research, they look for clues to see where the historical place is.When archeologists were finding Fort james, the National Park Serice led a five-year study of the area to figure out how the land was used. They used that information so they could know where to look for proof of the fort. That's what archeologist have to do to map out where the historical place is.                   When the archeologists find the historical place, they get their tools ready to dig. there are alot of tools they use on the site. Most archeologist start digging with a pick and shovel. They use it to dig in to the earth, close to the artifacts. Other main tools they use are whisk and dustpan ( to brush dirt off of the artifacts), knife ( used for careful digging and to scrape dirt from around the artifact), wheelbarrow ( used to move items from one place to another), skim shovel ( a shovel with a flat edge. It carefully remove thin layers of soil), and a trowel ( used to scrape and cut to view the different layers of soil).                    It takes years to accomplish your goal. Being an archeologist contains being patient. Your job is slow and tiresome so you have to be patient and steady. Even though it is tiresome, when you're done you'll know more about the historical place and you will find really cool things!

Archeologists have very important jobs. They help find the history of many people all over the world. There have been many important discoveries of important artifacts like finding Fort James and finding George Washington's childhood home. They also have many tools to dig up the past. There are many things to do if you are an archeologist.       One job the archeologists do is rediscovering old forts from the Revolutionary War like James Fort in Jamestown, Virginia. The Rediscovery Archaeological Project was ordered to find and rediscover the old James Fort. The fort was built in 1607 by English settlers. The archeologists found pieces of armor and weapons and the floor of the fort. They used computer mapping to find the exact location of the building.They made many maps of the fort.       Another job that many archeologists do is finding the homes or birthplaces of famous historians from all over the world. Many archeologists were interested in finding out more about George Washington's childhood. So they found the home that George Washington's father, Augustine Washington, moved his family to when George was six years old. The location of the house is now known as Ferry Farm. Since the house was actually gone, many archeologists believed that the base of the house was still there. So they started digging in 2003, and found the house in 2004, a year later. They found the kitchen, slave quarters, and the storage houses first. A few years later, they then found the main farmhouse.They had little proof that this really was the Washington household. They carefully used 3D computers to map the house out before the archeologists actually started digging.They also recorded what they found with the computer in the computer. They dug lightly and carefully and found the evidence they needed.       There are many tools that archeologists used to carefully dig up and move important artifacts. There are picks and shovels, which are used to dig into the Earth that is close to the artifact. A whisk and dustpan are used to dust dirt off of artifacts and pick up the dirt. A knife can be used to carefully dig and scrape dirt off of an artifact. A wheelbarrow is used to move artifacts or dirt to different places. A skim shovel is used to carefully remove thin layers of soil from the item. A trowel is probably the most common tool in archeology. It is used to scrape and cut soil to see the different layers.       In conclusion, archeologists do have difficult jobs, but they are important to world history. They help uncover important discoveries all over the world. I want to thank them for all of the history they reveal.

Being an archeologist takes a lot of hard work and determination. They also use a lot of tools in their work such as a whisk, dustpan, pick, shovel, trowel, knife, skim shovel, and a wheel barrow. A whisk and dustpan are used to brush dirt off and clear away dirt from the excavation site and arifacts. A pick and shovel of course dig to get to the artifacts while a trowel scrapes and cuts to view different types of soil. A skim shovel has a flat edge that is used to carefully remove thin layers of soil with each scoop. Also, a knife is used to scrape dirt away from around the artifacts. Finally, a wheelbarrow is used to carry dirt away from the excavation site or carefully carry artifacts. Archeologists At Work           ???Archeologists need to be carful and strong at their job because they have to dig up things. How do the archelogists find all these things? The process of digging on farms are carful ones. Each year many teams will work on them.       There can be up to 35 people on a team! The first team maps the area  using a 3D computer that can track underground. The information is recorded so that people will know what it looked like before people started digging.       Another team focuses on the actual digging, and the place the team does the digging is called a dig.Those archeologists start their dig with what are called skim shovels. These shovels are so small, flat and sharp they can remove thin layers of soil, one at a time. That soil is then placed in a box with a half-inch screen at the bottom. This lets dirt fall out while artifacts stay in.       The diggers also use a process called troweling. Troweling is when archeologists use small shovels, paint brushes and wooden picks to remove dirt. It can to two weeks a dig a 25 square foot section! Another team spends days in the lab studying the objects found. The whole process is tresome, but it's worth it.

Arceologists   By Mason Chipman   Part 1    The Dicovery of Jamestown        In 1994, a group people tried finding Jamestown. the main idea was to find some of the secrets and artifacts of Jamestown.        The fort was built in 1607 when settlers from England came to start a new life. At first they thought that the fort was built near the water, so it was easier to dock ships. Later they found out that Jamestown was further away from water for protection from enemy ships.        In 1861 the first objects were discovered. The people were called, arceologists. They found armer, weapons, and valuable things. 100 years later they found the exact spot where the fort was.        The National Park Service led a five- year study on the area to figure out what the land was used for. The people studying used computer software to look at the images there.        That's when they found Jamestown!!! The things they found first were markings on the ground. The markings showed where the walls used to be. The arceologists discovered that Jamestown was in the shape of a triangle. They discovered that it stretched all the way to the river. They  realized that there were stone ledges to hold canons. The arceologists found eleven cellars, dozens of burial sites, and ten buildings in where Jamestown stood.        Today , the group finds about 1 million things a year. Such as pottery, tools, coins, and metal toys that kids used to play with. In the 1600s, people in Jamestown also through their garbage  down wells that they didn't use. The arceologists found some of their garbage, it was mostly bones from animals they ate. The information helps use understand how people lived back then. We now know how the settlers beat the indians that often attacked Jamestown. We also know how they survived those many years many years without that much food.        It must have been a big acomplishment finding Jamestown. Maybe someday you can be arceologist. But something we do not know is his child hood.         We do know that he lived at Ferry Farm. The only thing is that there were four houses. They know there was a fire at his house. They also know that he smoked clay pipes which they found part of a clay pipe, so they have more proof that this is the right house. Now they know more about Washington's child hood. An archeologist has many jobs, such as digging, examining, and plotting. All these jobs are stated here in this essay:                  First, an archeologist digs for artifacts. He/she uses tools like picks, shovels, whisks, dustpans, knives, wheelbarrows, skim shovels, and trowels to dig for artifacts under the ground very easily, and quickly!                  Next, an archeologist examines ground for the remains of any forts, or ancient houses. This relates to Fort James and George Washington's house. Archeologists looked for remains of these ancient places, found their locations, and then dug!                  Finally, an archeologist might use computers to plot where things are underground. This way, he/she will know what they will dig for, and what is under them. If a giant water pipe that can easily be cracked is under them, they won't dig under them and create a giant water fountain! Instead, they will use the computers to find where something of a high cost is hidden. This way, they have a higher chance of finding a valuable ancient artifact quickly.                  As you can see, these are all the jobs that an archeologist does at work. These jobs are digging for artifacts, examining the ground for remains, and using computers to generate graphs of things under the ground. all these qualities used together, along with patience makes a archeologist successful.
